  "event_preview": "Charlotte Motor Speedway is a 1.5-mile (2.414 km) quad-oval in Concord, North Carolina, opened in 1960 with 24-degree banking in the turns and 5-degree banking on the straights. The North Carolina Education Lottery 200 is the tenth race of the 2026 NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series season, run over 134 laps (201 miles) with stage breaks at laps 45 and 90. Qualifying and practice were both cancelled due to rain, with the field set by owner points — Corey Day awarded the pole in the No. 7 Spire Motorsports Chevrolet, the same truck Kyle Busch drove to victory at Dover the previous weekend. The race weekend is also marked by the sudden passing of Busch, with Charlotte holding a moment of silence before the event. Caleb Costner is the only driver who failed to qualify, leaving a 36-truck field for the 134-lap race.\n\nKyle Busch is the all-time wins leader in the Truck Series at Charlotte, though his best result with Spire has been a fifth-place finish last May. Corey Heim, the defending winner, led 98 of 134 laps in the 2025 race en route to a dominant victory — his fourth win of that season.\n\nThe all-time Truck Series qualifying record at Charlotte belongs to Tanner Gray, who turned a 29.936-second lap (180.385 mph) to claim pole for the 2023 edition — the fastest qualifying lap the series has produced at the 1.5-mile oval."
